# --    Linux Fundimentals    -- #

#  System Information  #
  whoami	  Displays current username.
  id	  Returns users identity
  hostname	  Sets or prints the name of current host system.
  uname	  Prints basic information about the operating system name and system hardware.
  pwd	  Returns working directory name.
  ifconfig	  The ifconfig utility is used to assign or to view an address to a network interface and/or configure network interface parameters.
  ip	  Ip is a utility to show or manipulate routing, network devices, interfaces and tunnels.
  netstat	  Shows network status.
  ss	  Another utility to investigate sockets.
  ps	  Shows process status.
  who	  Displays who is logged in.
  env	  Prints environment or sets and executes command.
  lsblk	  Lists block devices.
  lsusb	  Lists USB devices
  lsof	  Lists opened files.
  lspci	  Lists PCI devices.

#  File Discriptors and File Redirections  #
  dpkg --list | grep "ii" | wc -l  dpkg is a somewhat universal package manager. "ii" indicates that that package is installed
  instead of using 2>/dev/null to get rid of permission denined use "2>1"
  Data Stream for Input
    STDIN – 0
  Data Stream for Output
    STDOUT – 1
  Data Stream for Output that relates to an error occurring.
    STDERR – 2

# Filter Contents #
  more  read contents of a file and can scroll
  less  same as more but lines disapear after exiting
  head  reads first 10 lines of a file
  tail  read last 10 lines of a file
  sort  sort the desired results alphabetically or numerically
  grep  only read lines in a file that have content you want
  cut   read contents of lines after something like ":" so if the line was "password:abcdefg" then it would return "abcdefg"
  tr    replace content in a line with one you specify ie. turn any ":" into a space when displaying the read
  column display more information about files and also oragnise them in a more readable way
  awk   display the first ($1) and last ($NF) result of the line
  sed   uses regex to subsitute specified objects from defines patterns
  wc    used to count items or lines in a file
